Both outputs are emitted and the transcript validates against `transcript_schema.json`.

**`transcript.json`** — 25 iterations, 106 hypotheses, 106 analyses, with all hypothesis_ids resolved, top-level fields set (`dataset_id="ds001_prostate"`, `model_id="claude-opus-4-7"`, `harness_id="claude-code@manual-iter"`, `max_iterations=25`).

**`analysis_summary.txt`** — narrative synthesis. Headline findings:

- **Olaparib × BRCA2 interaction is the only large, robust treatment–biomarker signal.** Adjusted interaction β ≈ +1.43 months (p < 1e-300). BRCA2+/olaparib+ mean PFS = 5.22 vs 3.67 for BRCA2+/olaparib−. Both olaparib and BRCA2 main effects collapse to ≈ 0 once the interaction is included — classic synthetic-lethality pattern.
- **Expected interactions that did NOT replicate:** pembrolizumab × MSI-high (p=0.27, wrong direction), Lu177-PSMA × PSMA-high (p=0.42), enzalutamide/abiraterone × AR-V7 (p>0.5).
- **Core prognostic spine:** ECOG (β=−1.15/unit), albumin (+0.49/g·dL⁻¹), log PSA (−0.38), log LDH (−0.10), weight loss (−0.075/%), ALP, mCRPC.
- **Surprising nulls:** patient-reported symptoms, comorbidities, race/ethnicity, prior therapy variables, NLR/CRP, most chemistry labs, and 10 surveyed SNPs all carried no incremental prognostic information beyond the spine above.
- **Age-suppression effect:** age has a positive PFS coefficient both univariably (+0.17 mo/yr) and adjusted, with near-zero correlation to other prognostic factors — likely a feature of the data-generating process (older patients selected for less aggressive disease).
